# SOLID Principles — Agent Architecture

## S — Single Responsibility Principle

Every module, class, and function has exactly one reason to change.

| Component | Responsibility | NOT Responsible For |
|---|---|---|
| `AgentController` | HTTP request/response, auth context extraction | Tool execution, LLM calls, verification |
| `AgentService` | Orchestrating the agent loop (LLM → tools → verification → response) | Individual tool logic, database queries |
| Each Tool class | Wrapping exactly one Ghostfolio service method, mapping I/O to tool schema | LLM reasoning, other tools, verification |
| `VerificationService` | Running verification checks against agent output | Tool execution, LLM calls |
| `RedactionService` | Sanitizing data before it enters the LLM context | Tool logic, verification |
| `ErrorMapperService` | Translating internal errors to user-facing messages | Business logic, tool execution |

When creating a new class, ask: "What is the single reason this class would need to change?" If the answer has an "and", split it.

## O — Open/Closed Principle

Software entities are open for extension but closed for modification.

- **Tool Registry:** Add new tools by creating a new tool file and registering it in the tool array. Never modify existing tools to accommodate a new one.
- **Verification Pipeline:** Add new checks by implementing the `VerificationCheck` interface. The pipeline iterates over all registered checkers — no switch/case on checker type.
- **Error Message Map:** Add new error types to the map object. Do not modify the mapper logic itself.

## L — Liskov Substitution Principle

Subtypes must be substitutable for their base types.

All tools return the same envelope:
```typescript
interface ToolResponse<T> {
  success: boolean;
  data?: T;
  error?: string;
}
```

All verification checkers implement the same interface:
```typescript
interface VerificationCheck {
  name: string;
  check(agentOutput: StructuredAgentResponse, toolOutputs: Map<string, ToolResponse<unknown>>): Promise<VerificationResult>;
}
```

Any code consuming tool output or verification results must work with the interface, never with a specific implementation.

## I — Interface Segregation Principle

Clients should not depend on interfaces they do not use.

- Tools depend on the specific Ghostfolio service methods they need, not on the entire service interface
- `AgentService` depends on tool definitions (name + schema + execute), not on tool internals
- The verification pipeline depends on `VerificationCheck`, not on individual checker implementation details

## D — Dependency Inversion Principle

High-level modules depend on abstractions, not low-level modules.

- Use NestJS Dependency Injection for all wiring — never `new ServiceName()` directly
- `AgentModule` declares its imports and providers; NestJS resolves the graph
- Mirror the existing `AiModule` pattern at `apps/api/src/app/endpoints/ai/ai.module.ts`
- Constructor injection for all services:

```typescript
@Injectable()
export class AgentService {
  constructor(
    private readonly portfolioService: PortfolioService,
    // ... other injected services
  ) {}
}
```

## Modular Design

One module per concern. Clear boundaries between:
- `agent/` — orchestration (AgentModule, AgentService, AgentController)
- `agent/tools/` — tool wrappers (one file per tool + registry)
- `agent/verification/` — verification pipeline (service + individual checkers)
- `agent/redaction/` — data sanitization
- `agent/errors/` — error mapping
- `agent/memory/` — conversation history
- `agent/prompts/` — system prompt definitions
- `agent/schemas/` — Zod schemas for tool I/O
- `agent/types/` — shared TypeScript interfaces
- `agent/formatters/` — response formatting
- `agent/eval/` — eval dataset and runner

## Degraded Path for Structured Output

When the LLM returns plain text instead of structured JSON:
- Return the narrative text directly to the user
- Run ONLY the RulesService (hallucination detection) verification
- Skip math consistency, source citation, and escalation checks
- Log the parse failure for prompt tuning
- This is a safe fallback, not a crash
